ustache clipped in the English fashion, very dependable-looking, very dapper in his frock coat and striped trousers. Podtyagin was regaling him with Maggi’s bouillon when Ganin entered. The air was tinged blue with cigarette smoke.

“Mr. Ganin—Mr. Kunitsyn.” Anton Sergeyevich, breathing heavily, his pince-nez twinkling, gently pushed Ganin into an armchair.

“This, Lev Glebovich, is my old schoolfellow who once wrote cribs for me.”

